## working with the cloud

being a web app, slidenotes is not allowed to directly access your local file system. instead, slidenotes automatically saves your changes into the cloud every 30 seconds—completely encrypted of course.

additionally, you can save to the cloud everytime you feel like it by simply pressing `ctrl` `s` (mac: `cmd` `s`) or by clicking on the **cloud menu** ![](cloudok) → **save to cloud now**.

## exporting and importing slidenotes

+++layout:left
###the file menu
![](filemenu)
*this menu lets you export and import to your local hard drive*
+++

the **file menu** gives you the option to export your slidenote and save it to your local file system.
you can choose between two formats: 
- **encrypted file** (ending on .slidenote) secured with a password of your choice
- **unencrypted text file** (ending on .md) 

if you want to keep working on your file locally by using another text editor, you should choose the unencrypted text file format.

images are encrypted and embedded *inside* the text so you only have one file.

the counterpart of that is the **import button**, which serves to open a encrypted slidenote or text file and import it into your slidenote—including embedded images of course.

in the **file menu** you can choose to export the presentation as an html file. the editor will then bake a ready-to-use html file of your slidenote with the current selected theme which can be opened by browsers. 
images are embedded inside the html so you only have one file. be aware that a lot of images will blow up the file size of the export.
 
you can choose to use encryption inside your slidenote, which makes it easy to exchange a presentation in a secure form via email or such. note that javascript is requiered to encrypted the html file when displayed in a browser.
 
if you choose a html file without encryption, we it is possible to open the slidenote with a browser which can't run javascript to have the most legacy support possible.
 
for those of you who know css: exporting as an html file has the advantage that you can alter its styles by hand before sending it to your audience.

![](publishmenu)
*manage your published presentations in the publish menu*
+++

+++layout
when you publish your slidenotes the current status of the slidenote—along with the theme you chose—gets transformed into a presentation an published online.

everything you publish will be encrypted and only accessible with:

1. a password of your choice *(if you leave it blank, the visitors of your presentation won't be asked for a password)*
2. a randomized url which is automatically generated for you

the visitory of your presentation do not need a slidenotes.io account.
so all you need to do is to share the url and the password with your audience. 

publishing on slidenotes.io has some extended features: 
- you and your audience can comment on the presentation by slide. this is a practical way of collecting feedback to your presentation. 
- you can host presentations online by controling the presentation of your audience in a multiuser presentation.

## holding a presentation online

sometimes it's nice to enrich a video conference with a live presentation. 
but often the quality of the video is not enough to fit for a presentation—who doesn't know the lag problem? *ah wait it's still blurry, i can't read a thing...*

well, slidenotes has a solution: instead of sharing the presentation via video stream, you can invite other people to join your presentation live and online.

just open a presentation you published on slidenotes.io, then press the **multi user button**![](multiuser) in the presentation controls down left. slidenote will present you a url to pass to your audience.

pass this url in the video conference, share your password for the presentation and everyone can open the same presentation but without the control buttons. 
now, whenever you change the slide so will their version of it.

no more blurry text—and even better: as slidenotes uses responsive designs, people can experience your presentation on any device.
